Correctness_Score: 1.0

Robustness_Score: 0.8
Reasoning: I ran the implementation against a brute-force solver on several deterministic cases (including the sample) and 200 randomized grids (sizes up to 5x5); outputs matched in all tests, supporting functional correctness. The algorithm (BFS over (cell,energy) with per-cell max-energy pruning) is a standard correct approach for this problem; omitting an explicit medicine-use bitmask is safe because reusing a medicine cannot strictly improve energy beyond its fixed value. Style is concise with a short explanatory comment and clear variable names but lacks more detailed documentation, hence 0.8. Simplicity is high — the solution is compact and efficient, with only a minor unused variable; robustness is good given problem constraints though worst-case state-space growth depends on energy values, so I rated it 0.8.
